article.headline: KG's 28 points, 17 boards lead the way
article.linkText: Garnett, T-Wolves win third in a row
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves weren't expecting their matchup with the Miami Heat to look good. They'll take the win, though, no matter how ugly. Kevin Garnett had 28 points and 17 rebounds for the Timberwolves, who earned a hard-fought 83-77 victory over the short-handed Heat on Saturday night. "It was a tough game," Minnesota's Mark Madsen said. "Like (general manager) Kevin McHale says, 'Every night is not a Mona Lisa." Sam Cassell added 18 points for the Timberwolves, who have won eight straight games at home and 15 of their last 18 overall. Brian Grant had 17 points and nine rebounds and Lamar Odom chipped in 15 points and 11 rebounds for the Heat, who dropped to 4-16 on the road and 1-9 on the road against the West. Their next four games (Sacramento, Utah, L.A. Clippers and Denver) are on the road against Western Conference teams. "We stuck with them the entire game and had a good chance to win," Grant said. "If we play this hard against the rest of the teams on the road, we'll give ourselves a chance." Ervin Johnson tied a season high with 10 points for Minnesota, which played one of its least impressive games in the last six weeks but was nonetheless relieved with a win after a scrappy effort by Miami. "We won," Cassell said. "That's the big thing about it." The Heat used only eight players and had just two healthy guards -- backup point guard Bimbo Coles sat out with a strained quadriceps and rookie Dwyane Wade is on the injured list with a sprained wrist. Malik Allen started in place of Caron Butler to give Miami some more size underneath. This was a classic Heat game, complete with the usual physical play in the paint, low shooting percentages and a final score well under 100. "Bump and grind," Cassell said. "That's Eastern Conference basketball." First-year coach Stan Van Gundy is searching for some consistency outside of Odom and Eddie Jones. Grant gave him some offense, but Jones -- Miami's leading scorer at more than 18 points per game -- was just 2-for-16 from the floor and finished with eight points. Second-to-last in the league in scoring, Miami lost for the fourth time in six games. Rafer Alston, the other half of the Heat's backcourt, had 12 points, nine assists and just one turnover in 42 minutes. "We played hard," Alston said. "We did everything we wanted to offensively and defensively." As if there were any doubt how valuable the Garnett-Cassell-Latrell Sprewell trio is to the Timberwolves, they showed it in the fourth quarter. Grant's jumper put the Heat up 73-72 with 6:34 left, but Garnett and Cassell sandwiched 17-footers around a missed 3-pointer by Jones. Garnett added a short bank shot to make it 78-73 Minnesota with 3:49 remaining. Sprewell struggled all night (he shot 2-for-12 and finished with seven points), but he drove the lane and dunked hard with 1:50 to go and give the Wolves an 81-75 advantage. Cassell made two free throws with 7.2 seconds left to put Minnesota ahead 83-77, its biggest lead. "As long as we win the game," Garnett said, "we don't care."

Game notes
Loren Woods, who spent the last two seasons with Minnesota as a little-used center, had 11 points and five rebounds for Miami. Woods had his first two shots blocked, the first by Garnett that drew a loud cheer, before converting a reverse layup against Oliver Miller. Late in the third quarter, Woods threw down an emphatic dunk and scowled at the crowd -- drawing boos. "They're upset I left," Woods said with a smirk. ... Timberwolves F Gary Trent, who sat out the second half Thursday against Portland after spraining his ankle, didn't play and is day-to-day for a three-game road trip next week. ... The Heat are 6-25 on the second day of back-to-back games. That's second-worst in the league since the beginning of last season. Toronto is 2-23. ... Minnesota (24-11) is five games ahead of last season's pace after 35 games.
